On **.NET 10 SDK**, you get **native MTP support** in `dotnet test` — no `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` property needed. That property is only for .NET 9 and earlier.

**Setup:** Add a `test` section to your `global.json`:

```json
{
  "sdk": {
    "version": "10.0.100"
  },
  "test": {
    "runner": "Microsoft.Testing.Platform"
  }
}
```

**Key differences from .NET 9:**

| .NET 9 (old way) | .NET 10 (new way) |
|---|---|
| `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` in Directory.Build.props | `"test": { "runner": "Microsoft.Testing.Platform" }` in global.json |
| Requires `--` separator: `dotnet test -- --report-trx` | Arguments pass directly: `dotnet test --report-trx` |

You still need the framework-specific runner property (`EnableMSTestRunner`, `EnableNUnitRunner`, etc.) and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` — the `global.json` setting only controls how `dotnet test` communicates with MTP, not whether your project builds as an MTP executable.

